12.body:
When using multiple nested loops (including while loops and for loops), you may want to break out of specific loops by labelling them. Note that the label starts with a single quote, but does not end with one. 'outer: loop { 'inner: while true { if condition { break 'outer; } else if other_condition { break 'inner; } }
}

3.body: Variables are defined with the let keyword, and compile-time constants with the const keyword. Variables are traditionally snake_case, and constants are SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE, just like in Python or C. let my_var = 32; const MY_CONST: usize = 32;
3.title: Defining Variables

4.body:
Types can (and may sometimes be required to) be explicitly stated by adding a colon, followed by the type, after the variable name. Note that all consts must be explicitly typed. // the ': u32' explicitly states that my_var has type `u32` (unsigned 32-bit integer)
let my_var: u32 = 32;
4.title: Explicit Types

5.body:
By default, all variables in Rust are immutable, and thus cannot be modified by any means (function calls, operations, etc.). To define a variable as mutable, you must use the mut keyword. Note that consts cannot be mutable, as they are constant. let mut my_var = 32;
my_var += 1;
5.title: Mutability
